Corridor

Target IP: 10.10.36.83
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Only HTTP application is open on the target machine.


Doing an aggressive scan against the HTTP application returns the result above.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this port via a web browser displays the web page above. When I hover over the thirteen doors, I notice I can click them. Each door links to a different page.


Viewing the source-code of this page contains the useful information above. Each door contains some type of hash.


Using the website hashes.com, I managed to obtain the plaintext of the hashes. According to this website, the hashes are of type MD5. Each door is labelled from one to thirteen in MD5 hash. What happens if I try to access a door that is not in the range between 1 and 13? I have to convert the input to MD5 first.

Exploitation & Flag


I tried to access the door 14 using the MD5 hash aab3238922bcc25a6f606eb525ffdc56, and I received the output above. Door 14 is not working. What about door 0?


And bingo! Browsing to door 0 at http://10.10.36.83/cfcd208495d565ef66e7dff9f98764da contains the flag flag{2477ef02448ad9156661ac40a6b8862e}. This was a fun IDOR challenge.
